This means the permutation must be split into two increasing subsequences such that each subsequence can be picked up in a single pass. 2. **Splitting the Permutation**: The permutation can be divided into two parts where the first part is an increasing sequence, and the remaining part (after the first part) is also an increasing sequence. This is because each pass picks up the smallest remaining cards from the left, and the remaining cards after each pass must also be in increasing order to allow the next pass to pick them up. 3. **Counting Valid Permutations**: The number of such permutations is equivalent to the number of ways to merge two increasing sequences. For a permutation of length \( n \), the number of such permutations is \( 2^{n-1} \).
